sequences","Cysteine disulfide bridges"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe correct answer is that collagen has \u003Cstrong\u003Eglycine at every third position\u003C/strong\u003E in its primary structure. This regular spacing of glycine is crucial because glycine is the smallest amino acid and must occur at every third position to allow the three polypeptide chains to wind tightly together to form the characteristic triple helix.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAlternating proline and hydroxyproline residues\u003C/strong\u003E - While these amino acids are common in collagen, they do not strictly alternate\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERandom distribution of amino acids\u003C/strong\u003E - Collagen has a highly ordered sequence with the repeating pattern Gly-X-Y\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELysine-rich repeating sequences\u003C/strong\u003E - While lysine residues are present and important for crosslinking, they are not the predominant feature of the sequence\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECysteine disulfide bridges\u003C/strong\u003E - Unlike many other proteins, collagen stability does not rely on disulfide bonds\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe characteristic Gly-X-Y repeating sequence, where X is often proline and Y is often hydroxyproline, allows the formation of a stable triple helix structure that gives collagen its strength.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Collagen molecules form a triple helix structure composed of three polypeptide chains.","The amino acid sequence glycine-X-Y repeats throughout the collagen chain, where X is often proline.","Glycine must occur at every third position for proper triple helix formation due to spatial constraints."],"references":["Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61801"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18606"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61801","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/61801"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-03T00:18:56+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-03T00:19:51+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11338"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76293"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4936","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4936"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udee1\ufe0f","name":"Immune System","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-10-17T23:16:52+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-27T10:23:44+10:30"},